    "title": "The Weight of the Unbroken Loaf",
    "text": "
      In the high passes of the **Bonepeak Mountains**, where the air is thin and the gods listen closely, there stood a lone waystation called **The Last Hearth**. Its keeper, **Eldrin the Silent**, was known for two things: his unbroken loaf of rye, passed down for generations, and his refusal to turn away any traveler—be they merchant, thief, or something worse.

      One winter, a stranger arrived at dusk, their face wrapped in frostbitten cloth, their breath reeking of iron. 'I claim shelter,' they rasped, pressing a silver coin into Eldrin’s palm. The coin bore no king’s mark, only a **serpent coiled around a dagger**. Eldrin hesitated—this was no ordinary guest—but the **Law of the Loaf** was absolute: *‘So long as the hearth burns, no traveler may be denied.’* He broke the sacred loaf in two, offering half to the stranger.

      That night, as Eldrin slept, the stranger stole not his coin, nor his food, but the **hearthstone itself**—the blackened rock at the fire’s heart, said to hold the first spark of the mountain’s sacred flame. When Eldrin awoke, the fire was cold, and the stranger gone. The villagers cried out in horror: *‘The hearth is dead! The gods will abandon us!’*

      Eldrin took up his staff and followed the stranger’s tracks into the blizzard. He found them at the **Cleft of the Forgotten**, where the stranger knelt, pressing the hearthstone into the snow. ‘Why?’ Eldrin demanded. The stranger turned, their face now a shifting mask of stolen visages. ‘Because your law is a chain,’ they hissed. ‘I break it to free the mountain.’

      But as the words left their lips, the snow beneath them **turned to ash**, and the hearthstone **burned white-hot**. The stranger screamed as the flame consumed them, leaving only the stone—and a single, unbroken loaf of rye at Eldrin’s feet. The villagers understood then: the **Law of the Loaf** was no mere custom, but a **covenant with the earth itself**. To break it was to invite the mountain’s wrath. And so, to this day, no traveler may pass the Bonepeaks without leaving an offering at The Last Hearth—**a loaf of their own, unbroken, in return for the sacred flame.**"
  }
}
```

