    "text": "
      In the **Valley of the Whispering Sands**, where the dunes sing with the voices of the forgotten, there stood a **caravanserai** called **The Last Thirst**. Its keeper, **Sylria the Unbroken**, was bound by a single rule: *‘No traveler shall leave my table with an empty cup.’* The rule was not kindness—it was **law**, carved into the doorpost in a tongue older than kings.

      One evening, a **hooded figure** arrived at dusk, their robes stained with the dust of distant roads. They carried no coin, only a **chipped clay cup**—the kind used by beggars in the **City of the Silent**. ‘I claim water,’ they said, voice like wind through dead reeds. Sylria hesitated. The cup was **cursed**; it had once belonged to **Veythas the Betrayer**, who had broken the sacred trust of the valley. But the law was absolute: to refuse a traveler water was to invite the **Drought of the Unseen**, a curse that turned wells to salt and tongues to ash.

      Sylria filled the cup from her own **sacred spring**, but as the water touched the clay, it **turned black**. The stranger drank deeply, then smiled—a smile too wide, too sharp. ‘You have given me what was owed,’ they said. ‘Now I take what was stolen.’ They seized the **spring’s stone**, the heart of the caravanserai’s power, and vanished into the night.

      Sylria pursued them to the **Dune of the Forgotten**, where the stranger knelt, pressing the stone into the sand. ‘Why?’ Sylria demanded. The stranger’s hood fell back, revealing a face **stitched from stolen memories**. ‘Your law is a chain,’ they hissed. ‘I break it to free the valley.’

      But as the words left their lips, the sand **turned to glass**, and the stone **burned white-hot**. The stranger screamed as the fire consumed them, leaving only the cup—and a single drop of water at Sylria’s feet. The villagers understood then: the **Oath of the Empty Cup** was no mere custom, but a **covenant with the earth itself**. To break it was to invite the valley’s wrath. And so, to this day, no traveler may pass the Whispering Sands without leaving an offering at The Last Thirst—**a cup of their own, filled to the brim, in return for the sacred trust.**"
  }
}
```

